[1] Europe ex Africa: GeoSentinel
Date: Wed 29 Jul 2020
From: David Hamer <dhamer@bu.edu> [edited]


COVID-19 acquired during travel to Africa
-----------------------------------------
As the COVID-19 pandemic continues to spread, all African countries have recorded infections and there are now more than 750 000 confirmed cases across the continent. Despite a range of prevention and containment measures against the pandemic, the number of reported new cases is increasing in countries like Algeria, South Africa, Egypt, Nigeria and Ghana. Because of limited availability of supplies and local capacity (similar to the situation in many high-income countries when the pandemic started), many countries face challenges conducting a sufficient number of tests and, therefore, there may be substantial under-reporting of COVID-19 cases. Infection in travelers can be a sentinel of high transmission rates.

In Europe, after an initial decrease of daily cases, some countries are now facing the daunting challenge of a potential 2nd wave. In France, the number of daily cases has started to rise again, and more than half of the cases hospitalized in ICUs during the past days in the Paris area are travel-associated, mainly returning from Africa.

In this respect, the following cases have been recently identified via the GeoSentinel Surveillance Network (June-July 2020):

- In Brescia (Italy): A VFR [visiting friends and relatives] traveler returning from Egypt is currently in the ICU with COVID-19.

- In Hamburg (Germany): COVID-19 cases were reported in 1 VFR traveler returning from Ghana and 2 sailors who acquired the infection during their landing in either Lagos or Dakar.

- In Paris (France): 8 new cases of COVID-19 occurred among travelers (5 returning from Algeria, 1 from Mauritania, 1 from the Central African Republic, 1 from Cameroon). All 8 were VFR travelers.

These data highlight the current risk of COVID-19 for visitors to Africa and the alarming threat for importation of the virus back to Europe and potentially other countries, which could contribute to a rebound of the epidemic.

The differences in cases we have observed among the 3 European counties may relate to differences in rules regarding returning travelers. France imposes a 14-day quarantine only for travelers returning from countries where a quarantine is demanded in return, regardless of the epidemic situation of the country. In Germany, a quarantine requirement is in place for those returning from regions designated by the Robert Koch Institute as high risk. Italy has kept the mandatory 14-day quarantine rule for all those arriving from a non-EU nation. Enforcement of quarantine measures is also likely to be variable among jurisdictions.

While closing European borders to travelers can be perceived as economically and politically complex, quarantine measures can be simple and effective and should be prioritized to limit the risk of ongoing transmission in Europe due to imported COVID-19 from Africa or elsewhere in the world where the pandemic remains highly active, such as North and South America.

--
Communicated on behalf of the GeoSentinel Surveillance Network by:

Oula Itani, MD
Eric Caumes, MD, PhD
Department of Infectious and Tropical Diseases, Sorbonne University
AP-HP, Pitie-Salpetriere Hospital
Paris, France

Sabine Jordan, MD
Bernard Knocht Institute
Hamburg, Germany

Francesco Castelli, MD, PhD
University of Brescia
Brescia, Italy

[ProMED would like to thank Drs. Itani, Caumes, Jordan and Castelli for submitting this report. This highlights the need for countries to establish quarantine procedures (including testing of asymptomatic individuals) for individuals arriving from outside their borders as part of control measures to prevent introduction of the SARS-CoV-2 with potential silent community spread. The countries of importation listed in the above report are countries that have all been flagged as having significant transmission of the virus at one point. Low-level reports from any country may not reflect significant silent transmission.

Countries that have markedly contained SARS-CoV-2 transmission see a shift from local transmitted cases to predominantly imported cases, and at some point have had multiple varying-sized clusters occur. As mentioned numerous times, this is a tenacious organism, most efficient in terms of stealth entry and transmission.

Again, many thanks to Drs. Itani, Caumes, Jordan and Castelli for submitting this report. - Mod.MPP]

